# Routing Architecture

This prototyping environment uses React Router v6 with HashRouter. Pages are accessed via hash URLs (e.g., `http://localhost:5174/#/home`).

## How It Works

- `src/App.tsx` is the router shell — skills manage it, designers don't edit it directly
- Each page lives in `src/pages/[Name].tsx`
- Each page has its own stylesheet at `src/styles/[Name].module.css`
- The `PAGES` array in `App.tsx` is the single source of truth for registered routes

## Adding a New Page

When creating a new page, do all four of these things in order:

1. Create `src/pages/[Name].tsx` — the page component
2. Create `src/styles/[Name].module.css` — the page stylesheet
3. Add an import to `App.tsx`: `import [Name] from './pages/[Name]'`
4. Add an entry to the `PAGES` array in `App.tsx`: `{ label: '[Label]', path: '/[path]', component: [Name] }`

After creating a page, always tell the designer: "Your new page is at `http://localhost:5174/#/[path]`"

## Page Naming Conventions

- **File names**: PascalCase with "Page" suffix — `SettingsPage.tsx`, `DashboardPage.tsx`
- **CSS files**: match the page file — `SettingsPage.module.css`
- **Paths**: lowercase, hyphenated — `/settings`, `/user-profile`
- **Labels**: title case, short — `Settings`, `User Profile`

## CSS Import in Page Files

Each page imports its own module CSS using a relative path from `src/pages/`:

```tsx
import styles from '../styles/SettingsPage.module.css'
```

Note the `../styles/` prefix — page files live one level deeper than `src/`.

## App.tsx Structure

```tsx
// App.tsx — Router shell. Skills manage the imports and PAGES array.
import { HashRouter, Routes, Route, Navigate } from 'react-router-dom'
import HomePage from './pages/HomePage'
import SettingsPage from './pages/SettingsPage'

const PAGES = [
  { label: 'Home', path: '/home', component: HomePage },
  { label: 'Settings', path: '/settings', component: SettingsPage },
]

export default function App() {
  return (
    <HashRouter>
      <Routes>
        <Route path="/" element={<Navigate to="/home" replace />} />
        {PAGES.map(({ path, component: Page }) => (
          <Route key={path} path={path} element={<Page />} />
        ))}
      </Routes>
    </HashRouter>
  )
}
```

## Styles Directory

```
src/styles/
├── App.module.css          ← Shell-level styles (minimal, for the router shell only)
├── HomePage.module.css     ← Home page styles
├── [Name].module.css       ← Per-page styles
├── index.css               ← Global styles (do not edit)
├── fonts.css               ← Font imports (do not edit)
└── intuit.css              ← IDS design tokens (do not edit)
```

## Navigation Between Pages

Navigation is part of the prototype, not a meta layer. There is no built-in nav shell — designers choose the right IDS navigation component for their use case and add it directly to their page components.

### Common Patterns

**Tabs navigation** — use `@ids-ts/tabs` with React Router's `useNavigate`:

```tsx
import { useNavigate, useLocation } from 'react-router-dom'
// In component:
const navigate = useNavigate()
const location = useLocation()
// Pass to Tabs: activeTab={location.pathname}, onTabChange={(path) => navigate(path)}
```

**Left sidebar navigation** — use `@ids-ts/left-navigation`:

```tsx
import { useNavigate, useLocation } from 'react-router-dom'
// Use location.pathname to set the active item, navigate(path) on item click
```

**Simple links** — use `@ids-ts/link` with React Router's `Link` component via the `as` prop, or use `useNavigate` in an `onClick` handler on a Button:

```tsx
import { Link as RouterLink } from 'react-router-dom'
import Link from '@ids-ts/link'
import '@ids-ts/link/dist/main.css'

// Option A: as prop
<Link as={RouterLink} to="/settings">Go to Settings</Link>

// Option B: navigate in onClick
const navigate = useNavigate()
<Button purpose="standard" priority="secondary" onClick={() => navigate('/settings')}>
  Go to Settings
</Button>
```

### Hash-Based URLs

Since the app uses HashRouter, all URLs are hash-based: `/#/page-name`. The `path` values in the `PAGES` array in `App.tsx` are relative (e.g. `'/settings'`) and the router handles the `#` prefix automatically. Link to pages using just the path — no need to add `#` manually.

### Tip for Designers

When a designer asks to "link" two pages or "add navigation", the right component depends on the design. Ask which IDS navigation pattern fits their prototype: tabs, left nav, breadcrumbs, pagination, or step flow. Each has a different use case and visual weight.

## Snapshot Awareness

Skills that snapshot the prototype must capture:
- `src/App.tsx`
- All files in `src/pages/`
- All `*.module.css` files in `src/styles/` (excluding `index.css`, `fonts.css`, `intuit.css`)
